4.3/5  rDev -3.4%look: 4 | smell: 4 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.25Picked this up a while back in New York, finally getting around to this tonight. Canned on 3/8 but still tasting fresh and without a lot of (big) floaties in this. Loved the other Grimm  Ales that I've had and once again, this was a "meal in a can" as this took a while to savor but only because this was so complex in flavor that I had to let it fully warm up. Beer like this demands a big block of time to enjoy it and to admire the Tommy Boy Records-like label!
Good pour to this as it came out golden, with the aforementioned floaties in here with a sufficiently thick head that didn't last for terribly long. Only a few thick cloud-like patches of lacing remained on the top third of my pint glass as the foam didn't stay around for terribly long either. Lots of marmalade, sweetness, candied sugar, and a fair amount of booze in the nose with more in the taste. Breaded malt, sweet malt, tropical fruits like melon and honeydew, were all in the taste to accompany a faint but lasting hop presence of pine and spruce. Low on carbonation, the malt stuck around in the aftertaste as the finish was quite clean here with a nice juicy and waxy coating staying in my mouth until the next sip. How these guys pack so much into one brew remained a mystery to me but there was a *lot* of depth to this that took a while to unravel. 
This was fairly strong but with so much going on here, you wouldn't even know it until the liquid was fully downed. IPA's are a dime a dozen, as I've stated in a ton of my reviews, but a beer like this almost calls to be placed into a category that doesn't even currently exist. Beer is sometimes referred to as "liquid bread" and after having this, it's easy to see why that nickname has been in existence for ages. Yet another offering and brewery killing it in the Big Apple right now! 1,820 charactersJerzDevl2000, Jun 23, 2016
